  "contentData": [
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/6da25b1564d94daf85033a3a909b25f6",
      "title": "Why QMU?",
      "content": "<ul>\n<li>Dialogue is at the heart of public sociology – a dialogue between sociology and the people and communities that are trying to make the world a better place.</li>\n<li>Learn from staff with a wide range of experience in community settings outside the university, including with young people, mental health, environmental campaigns, community education, gender justice and queer activism.</li>\n</ul>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/12369c925b81440abda5eba19ae7601b",
      "title": "Course overview",
      "content": "<p>Essentially, public sociology is about understanding society and how to bring about change. It actively brings sociology into dialogue with audiences beyond the classroom. By creating this active, open dialogue it aims to deepen both sides’ understanding of public issues.</p>\n<p>Sociological knowledge theory, analysis and social practice are directly connected to the experiences of particular ‘publics’, normally  understood as community groups, interest groups, campaigns or other civil society organisations. Public sociology is a discipline that speaks to, and for, udiences and communities beyond the parameters of the academic discipline and makes meaningful contributions to ongoing debates around public issues and concerns.</p>\n<p>This course offers you the opportunity to engage with diverse public groups and to reflect critically on how sociology can contribute to work for social justice and change. You will study what is distinctive about public sociology and the methods of engagement and research of the discipline.</p>\n<p>Public sociology is a contextual discipline responding to globalisation. The course draws on the experiences of public sociologists throughout the world and involves teaching by academics from a range of disciplines in which public sociology is relevant. Lecturers are engaged in research, education and activism with various public groups.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/b6bad882bec044119d68520586e11e95",
      "title": "Exit awards",
      "content": "<p>PgCert (60 credits)</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/fa96a979bcca40a8b7dc29dbd812e321",
      "title": "Structure",
      "content": "<p>You can opt to study for the PgCert or you can also register as an associate student to complete a single module for CPD.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/b308029574de4515a5497208eafd6a65",
      "title": "Teaching, learning and assessment",
      "content": "<p>The course structure involves online lectures and seminars, self-directed study and, where feasible, seminars on campus for one day per week over 10 weeks. It is possible to complete this programme entirely online if desired.</p>\n<p>You will attend lectures and seminars, work in groups, as well as carry out independent learning. You will be expected to participate in discussions, collaboratively develop ideas and engage with experiential learning. It is particularly expected that you will be engaged with a ‘public’, either through personal experience, employment or voluntary commitment, to reflect on the sociological contribution to that work.</p>\n<p>We offer a range of stimulating assessment methods, including blogs, reflections on practice, live debates, group work with presentations as well as essays and field reports.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/edbe38a5c5d34f49bbfa14ac0b64a406",
      "title": "Teaching hours and attendance",
      "content": "<p>Each module will require you to attend classes and carry out independent work. Most modules consist of two to three hours of class time each week of the semester and will involve input, critical reading, debate and reflection on experience. Where possible, all teaching takes place over two days per week. Your specific timetable will depend on whether you study full-time or part-time.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/d80cd6f3c73e490ba96a4185698d37d6",
      "title": "Class sizes",
      "content": "<p>Some of the modules in this programme are shared with other programmes, however class size is not expected to exceed 15.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/d0b4af80280a43dbb9bc434bebb66578",
      "title": "Industry links",
      "content": "<p>Teaching staff have a range of links with community, voluntary sector and campaign groups in civil society. This has included Friends of the Earth, Glasgow Association for Mental Health, the Workers’ Educational Association, the International Campaign for Justice in Bhopal, and various faith-based, trade union and European social policy organisations.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/45f2809e82b14c4f952693eeca25896b",
      "title": "Modules",
      "content": "<ul>\n<li><strong>Principles of Public Sociology (20 credits):</strong> an introduction to social analysis</li>\n<li><strong>Public Sociology Practice (20 credits):</strong> how social analysis contributes to a range of professional, community action and social movement practices</li>\n<li><strong>Reflection on Action (20 credits): </strong>an opportunity to reflect systematically on the relationship between practice and theory</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The modules listed are correct at time of posting (October 2021) but are subject to change. In the event that modules change, QMU will seek to use reasonable endeavours to ensure that there is no detrimental impact on students.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/8f589f35c44a491981e6ee2f71348654",
      "title": "Single modules for CPD",
      "content": "<p>Available. Register as an associate student to study single modules in areas of interest. Contact <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"mailto:escandrett@qmu.ac.uk\" target=\"_blank\">Eurig Scandrett</a> for more information.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/1955c97b7acd4e60b0748e3a768be15d",
      "title": "Placements",
      "content": "<p>There are no formal placements on this course but students are expected to engage with a community group, campaign or representative organisation throughout their studies. It is not a placement as such, but students should take responsibility for this as their own engagement with public sociology. Ideally, students will already be involved, or have been involved, with such a group, although we appreciate that this is not always possible. Advice and assistance will be provided for students who start the course without suitable public engagement.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/01e69debeb6646dbaa9926c96f41c64d",
      "title": "Careers",
      "content": "<p>Graduates of public sociology will be suitably qualified for a range of careers involving public engagement in the public or third sector or in non-governmental organisations.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/c95590cba5354d0f9319924fe9784da3",
      "title": "Entry requirements",
      "content": "<p>Degree and/or relevant experience of engagement with communities or public groups. We will consider applications from people without a degree but with significant experience of community work or similar, and who can show that they are able to study at postgraduate level.</p>\n<p>International: You will be required to provide evidence of English language competence at no less than IELTS 6.5 with no individual component score below 6.0.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/98e70a7c921c4deeb626220af643dcc9",
      "title": "Application deadline",
      "content": "<p>This course is no longer available for February 2023 entry.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/01f0fb9a7da54908b93882d8445175d5",
      "title": "More information and contacts",
      "content": "<p>Contact <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"mailto:admissions@qmu.ac.uk\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Contact Admissions\">Admissions</a> or contact Programme Leader, <a rel=\"noopener\" href=\"mailto:escandrett@qmu.ac.uk\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Contact Eurig Scandrett\">Eurig Scandrett</a> </p>\n<p> </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/eadd8b1f56c6421890e1dbf2269dc97a",
      "title": "Opportunities to meet us",
      "content": "<p><a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/fde923ae229e4d59916e57b4c164f7c1}\" title=\"Open Days and Meeting Us\">Click for information on our forthcoming open events</a></p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/e7df818546474b83acd1fb7147ecc06c",
      "title": " Fees and transitionary scholarships for postgraduate EU students in 21/22 and 22/23:",
      "content": "<p>As part of our management of the Brexit transition, for many of our courses, including this one, we have introduced an EU transitional scholarship for EU full-time postgraduate students commencing their studies on campus in academic years 2021/22 and 2022/23. This provides a 40% discount on international tuition fees. The scholarship is available to EU students for whom the international fee rate applies and covers the courses marked with a # in the <a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/76213294d5cd485fa1723ccb1c813ca2}\" title=\"Postgraduate Funding\">Postgraduate Fees – Full-Time Study section of our Fees page</a>. This transitional scholarship is not applicable to students from the Republic of Ireland, who will continue to be eligible for the home fee rate.</p>"
    }
  ],
